 To get a C:
o
o The elevator that I am evaluating can be found at the 25Twenty apartment
complex. The control interface design is simplistic, but the numbers are arranged
side by side in columns of two, which is a bit unintuitive.
 To get a B:
o Common uses of elevator: go up, go down, open door button
o Rare uses: emergency button, close door button
o The interface makes doing these common things rather easy, but also provides the
option to do less common activities as well.
o In order to get the elevator to move to a particular floor, the user simply needs to
press a numbered button. The button layout is a bit unintuitive but can quickly be
understood. Once a floor is selected, the elevator will begin to move up or down.
The elevator also provides a braille interface to aid those with visual disabilities.
When a button is pressed, the elevator provides feedback by lighting up the button
and playing a sound. Due to the layout of the elevator buttons, selecting the wrong
floor is an easy mistake to make. The only suggestion I could make to improve
the design is to align the elevator floor buttons vertically. That way, its easier to
understand how to navigate the building floors.
o
